{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":3850,"record_hash":"sha256:3ad88ee3ad20019cc5b791772db09850095bd4dbb5c8c77eeb1fbb68150003a5","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:24:06.070Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Searched. Yes, there are options, but I’d be a little careful here.\n\nBest candidates I found:\n\n- [`hazler-secrets`](https://docs.rs/hazler-secrets/latest/hazler_secrets/) looks closest to “small Rust library we embed.” It has a `SecretScanner`, Shannon entropy scanning, and findings include line, column, `matched_text`, type, severity, and context. That gives us enough to mask transcript strings without writing our own detector.\n- [`secretscan`](https://docs.rs/secretscan/latest/secretscan/) is also a Rust lib/CLI and exposes entropy helpers like `entropy::is_high_entropy` plus scanner APIs, but it looks younger and more scanner-tool shaped.\n- [`gitleaks`](https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks) is the mature choice, supports stdin scanning, entropy rules, JSON/SARIF reports, and redaction flags, but it’s Go, not a Rust library. We’d have to shell out or vendor a binary, which feels too much for this POC.\n- [`ripsecrets`](https://docs.rs/crate/ripsecrets/0.1.11) is interesting and local-only, but it presents primarily as a CLI and docs coverage is basically absent, so less pleasant as an embedded dependency.\n\nMy pragmatic take: for this POC, if we do it, I’d spike `hazler-secrets` behind the existing `agentlog` feature and only apply it when `--include-transcript` is used. We would not implement detection ourselves; we’d only do the boring transformation step: scan serialized transcript record text, replace detected `matched_text` with something like `[REDACTED:secret]`, and store the redacted `source_record`.\n\nOne important design wrinkle: dedupe hashes should still be computed from the original raw transcript record, but stored transcript envelopes would contain redacted content. That’s fine, but we should make it explicit with a field like `source_record_redacted: true` or a small `redactions_count`, so nobody assumes the stored `source_record` byte-for-byte matches `source_record_hash`.\n\nI’d avoid gitleaks/subprocess for now. Great tool, wrong shape for “keep the POC small.”","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:24:06.070Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}